WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.280
I'm Melissa, and today I'm going to be talking about how to achieve a seamless workflow

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:14.880
between R, Python and SAS, all from within RStudio.

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:19.480
Now we're at an RStudio conference, and more specifically, right now, we're in a session

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:22.799
that's called Some of my best friends use Python.

00:00:22.799 --> 00:00:27.680
So I already know that everyone in this room loves at least three of the words that are

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:30.719
in the title of my talk.

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:34.959
But before we talk about R or Python, I first want to take a moment to talk about something

00:00:34.959 --> 00:00:42.160
that I know we're all even more passionate about, which, of course, is SAS.

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:47.200
Don't worry, I'm totally kidding, I was not referring to SAS here at all, I was actually

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:49.380
talking about food.

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:52.639
And I apologize in advance, because I know we're still about an hour away from our lunch

00:00:52.639 --> 00:00:57.119
break today, but I do just want to take a moment to talk about food before we go any

00:00:57.119 --> 00:00:58.880
further.

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:02.279
I love food, but I'm not a very good cook.

00:01:02.279 --> 00:01:05.639
So I really like these meal kit boxes that you can get delivered to your door, because

00:01:05.639 --> 00:01:09.919
the recipes are always super straightforward, and they always come with the exact right ingredients

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:13.559
measured out in the exact right proportions.

00:01:13.559 --> 00:01:17.879
And usually if I follow along with the steps in the recipe in one of these meal kit boxes,

00:01:17.879 --> 00:01:23.040
I can get the results to look pretty close to the pictures that are in the recipe.

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:26.879
But there's just one problem with these meal kit boxes.

00:01:26.879 --> 00:01:33.980
And that problem is that they give bad cooks like me false confidence.

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:38.360
These meal kit boxes have me thinking that I'm totally capable of recreating these masterpieces

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:43.879
totally on my own, but a few weeks later, if I try to reproduce the food, I don't have

00:01:43.879 --> 00:01:48.519
all of the ingredients available, and suddenly I have to start making some substitutions,

00:01:48.519 --> 00:01:56.239
and all of a sudden my food can end up looking a little more something like this.

00:01:56.239 --> 00:02:00.480
And I find that the same can be said for a lot of programming tutorials.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:04.599
If you have all of the right ingredients measured out in the exact right proportions, then it's

00:02:04.599 --> 00:02:09.539
pretty easy to follow along with a simple recipe and get the desired results.

00:02:09.539 --> 00:02:13.399
But if you're missing some key ingredients, then you start having to make some substitutions

00:02:13.399 --> 00:02:17.600
or find some workarounds, and then you'll end up with something that's perhaps technically

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:22.100
edible, although certainly less than ideal.

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:24.919
And that leads me to the outline for my talk today.

00:02:24.919 --> 00:02:28.960
I'm going to be discussing how to incorporate these three languages into your workflow,

00:02:28.960 --> 00:02:32.679
but I'm going to present it in two different ways.

00:02:32.679 --> 00:02:37.199
The first way is an ideal approach, and this approach is going to be kind of like following

00:02:37.199 --> 00:02:43.000
along with a simple three-step recipe, but the downside here is that I'm going to assume

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.080
that you have all of the ingredients available.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.960
And the second way that I'll present is a less than ideal approach, where you're missing

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:54.000
some key ingredients, and so you have to find some workarounds.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.800
But before I jump into that, I first want to start by providing some context as to why

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:02.960
this particular challenge arose for me.

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:07.919
I'm an analyst at Statistics Canada, which, for those who are unfamiliar, is an agency

00:03:07.919 --> 00:03:13.899
within the government of Canada, and Statistics Canada is Canada's official statistical agency.

00:03:13.899 --> 00:03:19.460
And the particular challenge that I face at work is that my employer wants to adopt open-source

00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:26.360
programming languages like R and Python, but we have a legal responsibility to ensure that

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:33.059
personal information collected for statistical purposes is kept strictly confidential.

00:03:33.059 --> 00:03:37.199
This means that when we publish statistics, we first need to use an internal generalized

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:42.539
system called GConfid, which is a series of SAS macros that prevents the release of

00:03:42.539 --> 00:03:47.360
confidential information in tabular data using cell suppression and controlled random rounding

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:49.759
methods.

00:03:49.759 --> 00:03:54.919
And GConfid is only implemented in the SAS programming language.

00:03:54.919 --> 00:04:00.039
And what this means in practice is that many analysts and data scientists at Statistics

00:04:00.039 --> 00:04:05.320
Canada have to use SAS as part of their workflow if they want to be able to publish official

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:08.039
statistics.

00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:12.600
My typical workflow at StatCan usually looks a little bit something like this.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:17.200
I work with some SAS datasets that first get passed through some pre-written preprocessing

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:19.839
scripts that are written in SAS.

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:24.079
And once the data are ready to be analyzed, I bring the data into R, and then I do the

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:28.440
vast majority of my analysis in R.

00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:33.239
But if I want those results to be publishable, then I need to bring the data from R back

00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:37.640
into SAS so that I can use these GConfid macros.

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:40.839
And you can think of GConfid kind of like a black box.

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:45.959
It's a series of SAS macros that is completely uneditable by me, and these macros are themselves

00:04:45.959 --> 00:04:47.160
confidential.

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:53.000
So I cannot and I would not want to implement GConfid in any other programming language.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So for this step, I really do need to use SAS.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.359
Once I'm finished with GConfid, I bring those results back into R for data visualization

00:05:01.359 --> 00:05:03.040
purposes.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:07.480
And as you can see, my workflow really does require me to be able to go back and forth

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:10.640
between SAS and R seamlessly.

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:15.359
And while I myself don't typically use Python at work, I do have a lot of colleagues who

00:05:15.359 --> 00:05:19.559
would appreciate the ability to incorporate it into their workflow.

00:05:19.559 --> 00:05:25.339
So all of this led me to the question, is there a way to combine these three languages

00:05:25.339 --> 00:05:30.640
in the same script in a way that does not cause a headache?

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:33.959
And the answer is yes, and there are multiple different approaches.

00:05:33.959 --> 00:05:39.200
The most straightforward approach is a simple three-step recipe, and step one of this recipe

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:42.399
is to gather your required ingredients.

00:05:42.399 --> 00:05:46.160
For this particular recipe, the required ingredients are the languages that you're interested in

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:49.040
using plus Java.

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:52.920
And the other ingredient that's not pictured here, but which really is the most important

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:57.959
ingredient for making this particular recipe succeed is admin privileges.

00:05:57.959 --> 00:06:01.799
And if you don't have admin privileges on your computer, you might not be able to get

00:06:01.799 --> 00:06:05.040
this recipe to work.

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:09.100
Step two of this three-step recipe, assuming you have all of those required ingredients

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:14.959
from step one, is to install SASPy, which is a Python package that works very similarly

00:06:14.959 --> 00:06:17.359
to how Reticulate works.

00:06:17.359 --> 00:06:24.359
So just like Reticulate is an R interface to Python, SASPy is a Python interface to

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:26.679
SAS.

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:33.399
The third and final step of this three-step recipe is to perform a couple of system configurations.

00:06:33.399 --> 00:06:36.440
And there's a lot of little details that are in this step, so I won't go over that today

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:42.279
for the sake of time, but if you're interested in following along, there is a video on my

00:06:42.279 --> 00:06:47.200
YouTube channel that explains all of the steps and includes an example usage of combining

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:52.480
these three languages in the same script using SASPy.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:56.640
Now that was definitely the most straightforward approach and the recommended, well, my personal

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:01.160
recommended way of how to achieve this workflow, but if you have limited control over your

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:03.959
computer, then it might not be possible for you.

00:07:03.959 --> 00:07:07.880
So in the next few slides, I'm going to present a few alternative approaches that will allow

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:13.720
you to combine SAS and R in the same script, and sometimes Python.

00:07:13.720 --> 00:07:17.760
The approach that you choose is going to depend heavily on what you need to do and on how much

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:20.359
control you have over your computer.

00:07:20.359 --> 00:07:24.559
And for the three alternative options that I'm about to present, for all three of them,

00:07:24.559 --> 00:07:30.640
there's going to be a big tradeoff between complexity and usefulness.

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:35.239
The first option is to use the SAS Markdown package, which, as you might be able to guess

00:07:35.239 --> 00:07:40.480
from the name, is a package that allows you to include SAS chunks in your R Markdown or

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:42.880
Cordo documents.

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:47.279
This option has the benefit of not requiring admin privileges, but the downside is that

00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:51.559
there's no interaction between SAS and R at all.

00:07:51.559 --> 00:07:56.480
So what this means is that the SAS data sets that you define in your SAS chunks are not

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:00.679
going to be accessible to you in your R chunks and vice versa.

00:08:00.679 --> 00:08:06.079
For me personally, I really need this interoperability between these two languages, so this particular

00:08:06.079 --> 00:08:10.359
option isn't the most useful for me, but this package does have some really interesting

00:08:10.359 --> 00:08:11.959
use cases.

00:08:11.959 --> 00:08:16.500
For example, if you're a course instructor, you could use this in order to show your students

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:20.940
how to perform the same task using multiple different programming languages all in the

00:08:20.940 --> 00:08:23.019
same place.

00:08:23.019 --> 00:08:27.260
Once you have the SAS Markdown package installed, it's fairly easy to switch between the three

00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:32.039
languages within your R Markdown or Cordo documents, and all you need to do is specify

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:36.859
which language you'd like to use in each individual code chunk.

00:08:36.859 --> 00:08:42.780
If you want to use SAS, just set the engine option to be SAS HTML, and you can set the

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:48.900
engine path option to be the file path to your SAS executable.

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:54.619
To use R, leave the chunk header as the default, and to use Python, set the chunk header to

00:08:54.619 --> 00:08:56.340
say Python.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:09:00.020
And if you were to knit an R Markdown document that contains three chunks that looks like

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:07.400
this, the result will be something that looks like this.

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:12.359
The second approach that you can use is a SAS-first approach rather than an R-first

00:09:12.359 --> 00:09:14.159
approach.

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:19.119
When SAS is launched, there's an option that you can enable, which is called RLANG.

00:09:19.119 --> 00:09:23.960
And the RLANG that you see there on the slide in all caps, I should mention, has absolutely

00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:29.719
no relationship to the RLANG package in R. So this all caps RLANG that you see here is

00:09:29.719 --> 00:09:33.200
a SAS concept, not an R concept.

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:38.280
The RLANG option can be enabled without admin privileges, and it's pretty easy to move data

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:42.559
back and forth between SAS and R using this method, which makes this option quite a bit

00:09:42.559 --> 00:09:48.640
more useful than the SAS Markdown package, for my purposes at least.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:55.119
Once the RLANG option is enabled, you can use proc IML in SAS to execute R code.

00:09:55.119 --> 00:10:00.880
And in order to execute that R code, just use a submit statement with the R option enabled.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:04.880
And then anything that you put between the submit and end submit lines will be executed

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:09.000
as R code rather than as SAS code.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:13.119
Now I mentioned that it's pretty easy to move data back and forth between R and SAS.

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:19.000
And if you want to go from R to SAS, you can use the import data set from R subroutine.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:24.760
And if you want to go in the opposite direction, so to go from SAS to R, use the export data

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:27.280
set to R subroutine.

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:29.919
Both of these subroutines use the exact same syntax.

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:34.080
You start by specifying the name of the SAS data set, and then specify the name of the

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:36.239
R data frame.

00:10:36.239 --> 00:10:41.000
I mentioned before that this option doesn't require admin privileges, but really that's

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:42.919
only partially true.

00:10:42.919 --> 00:10:47.359
If you want to use this method from base SAS, then you don't need to have admin privileges

00:10:47.359 --> 00:10:50.239
in order to enable this RLANG option.

00:10:50.239 --> 00:10:54.960
But if you're like me, and if you prefer to use an IDE like SAS Enterprise Guide, then

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:59.760
you will need admin privileges in order to enable this feature.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:03.880
If you are interested in using this method from within SAS Enterprise Guide, there's

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:09.799
a video on my YouTube channel that goes through the full instructions of how to set this up.

00:11:09.799 --> 00:11:14.880
The third option that I'm going to talk about today is the one that is the most complex,

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:19.359
but also the one that's the most useful if what you really need is the interoperability

00:11:19.359 --> 00:11:24.900
between SAS and R, and if you don't have admin privileges, and if you want to be working

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:27.880
from within RStudio.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:31.000
And this is actually the approach that I was using myself at work for the past couple

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:32.400
of months.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:37.200
Myself and a coworker on my team, as well as a colleague from another part of our organization,

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:41.760
worked together to develop an internal R package that contains a function that allows you to

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:48.599
take an R data frame, manipulate it in SAS, and then return the results to R as an R data

00:11:48.599 --> 00:11:53.359
frame without ever leaving RStudio.

00:11:53.359 --> 00:11:56.679
And this package is not publicly available, but you can easily come up with a similar

00:11:56.679 --> 00:12:02.280
solution using the same general underlying principles that I'm about to show you.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:05.840
The first argument that this function takes is the name of the R data frame that you'd

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:11.400
like to manipulate in SAS, and here I'm just using the MT cars dataset, which is a dataset

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:16.679
that comes built into R and includes variables about characteristics of cars, such as miles

00:12:16.679 --> 00:12:20.919
per gallon, horsepower, cylinders, and so on.

00:12:20.919 --> 00:12:25.359
The second argument that this function takes is the location to the SAS installation on

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:30.960
your machine, and the final argument that this function takes is the SAS code that you'd

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:35.200
like to apply to your R data frame.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:39.960
This function assumes that in SAS you have access to a dataset that's called in underscore

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:45.799
df, and then the SAS dataset that will eventually get sent back to the user as an R data frame

00:12:45.799 --> 00:12:49.179
is called out underscore df.

00:12:49.179 --> 00:12:54.900
And the example that I'm using here, I'm just using the frequency procedure in SAS to create

00:12:54.900 --> 00:13:00.299
a frequency table of the cylinder variable from the MT cars dataset.

00:13:00.299 --> 00:13:05.960
And by executing just those two lines of code, the results from SAS are brought to the user

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:11.200
in RStudio without ever having had to exit RStudio.

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:14.719
In terms of the actual implementation of this function, this function starts by creating

00:13:14.719 --> 00:13:21.640
a temporary file folder and then saving the user inputted R data frame as a dot RDS file

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:24.440
in that temporary file folder.

00:13:24.440 --> 00:13:30.679
From here, a temporary SAS program is created, and the user inputted SAS code is then inserted

00:13:30.679 --> 00:13:36.799
into that temporary SAS program, making use of proc IML and the import dataset from R

00:13:36.799 --> 00:13:41.500
and export dataset to R subroutines that we talked about a little bit earlier.

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:47.640
This temporary SAS program is then executed by sending a command to the command prompt,

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:52.280
enabling the Rlang option, and then the temporary files are deleted after the results are brought

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:53.679
back into R.

00:13:53.880 --> 00:14:01.440
And finally, the results are returned to the user as an R data frame.

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:08.400
We all love R, but there might be times where we want or need to use other programming languages.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:12.599
Tools like SASPy are making this easier than ever to combine multiple languages in the

00:14:12.599 --> 00:14:18.159
same place, but if these options are unavailable or infeasible to you for whatever reason,

00:14:18.679 --> 00:14:24.000
you might be able to find some clever workarounds if you're willing to put in the work.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.359
For me, it's been a little over a year of exploring all these different options and

00:14:28.359 --> 00:14:32.919
more in order to figure out what's viable for me in my workplace, and I'm very happy

00:14:32.919 --> 00:14:37.679
to say that as of two weeks ago, some changes to our IT infrastructure have resulted in

00:14:37.679 --> 00:14:44.479
Statistics Canada employees being able to use SASPy without any issues at all.

00:14:44.479 --> 00:14:45.479
Thank you so much for listening.

00:14:45.479 --> 00:14:49.799
I'd be super happy to connect on LinkedIn or wherever if you want to chat about this more.

